[src:spacecraft-guidance/guidance-navigation-and-control] Today's complex systems use multiple approaches to determine current position.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/guidance-navigation-and-control] data in the boost phase and relative position data for intercept targeting.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/guidance-navigation-and-control] Complex systems typically have multiple redundancy to address drift, improve accuracy (ex. relative to a target) and address isolated system failure.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/guidance-navigation-and-control] Navigation systems therefore take multiple inputs from many different sensors, both internal to the system and/or external (ex. ground based update).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/guidance-navigation-and-control] provides the most common approach to combining navigation data (from multiple sensors) to resolve current position.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/guidance-navigation-and-control] It takes input from the navigation system (where am I) and uses targeting information (where do I want to go) to send signals to the flight control system that will allow the vehicle to reach its destination (within the operating constraints of the vehicle).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/guidance-navigation-and-control] The "targets" for guidance systems are one or more state vectors (position and velocity) and can be inertial or relative.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/guidance-navigation-and-control] During powered flight, guidance is continually calculating steering directions for flight control.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/guidance-navigation-and-control] targets an altitude, velocity vector, and gamma to drive main engine cut off.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/guidance-navigation-and-control] The target vectors are developed to fulfill the mission and can be preplanned or dynamically created.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/guidance-navigation-and-control] Flight control is accomplished either aerodynamically or through powered controls such as engines.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/guidance-navigation-and-control] Guidance sends signals to flight control.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/guidance-navigation-and-control] A Digital Autopilot (DAP) is the interface between guidance and control.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/guidance-navigation-and-control] Guidance and the DAP are responsible for calculating the precise instruction for each flight control.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/guidance-navigation-and-control] The DAP provides feedback to guidance on the state of flight controls.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/guidance-navigation-and-control] GNC systems are found in essentially all autonomous or semi-autonomous systems.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The filter is constructed as a mean squared error minimiser, but an alternative derivation of the filter is also provided showing how the filter relates to maximum likelihood statistics.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering has numerous technological applications.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] A common application is for guidance, navigation, and control of vehicles, particularly aircraft, spacecraft and ships positioned dynamically.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Furthermore, Kalman filtering is much applied in time series analysis tasks such as signal processing and econometrics.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering is also important for robotic motion planning and control, and can be used for trajectory optimization.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering also works for modeling the central nervous system's control of movement.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Due to the time delay between issuing motor commands and receiving sensory feedback, the use of Kalman filters provides a realistic model for making estimates of the current state of a motor system and issuing updated commands.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The algorithm works via a two-phase process: a *prediction phase* and an *update phase*.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] In the prediction phase, the Kalman filter produces estimates of the current state variables, including their uncertainties.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Once the outcome of the next measurement (necessarily corrupted with some error, including random noise) is observed, these estimates are updated using a weighted average, with more weight given to estimates with greater certainty.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] It can operate in real time, using only the present input measurements and the state calculated previously and its uncertainty matrix; no additional past information is required.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Optimality of Kalman filtering assumes that errors have a normal (Gaussian) distribution.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Kálmán, "The following assumptions are made about random processes: Physical random phenomena may be thought of as due to primary random sources exciting dynamic systems.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] It is a common misconception (perpetuated in the literature) that the Kalman filter cannot be rigorously applied unless all noise processes are assumed to be Gaussian.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Extensions and generalizations of the method have also been developed, such as the extended Kalman filter and the unscented Kalman filter which work on nonlinear systems.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The basis is a hidden Markov model such that the state space of the latent variables is continuous and all latent and observed variables have Gaussian distributions.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering has been used successfully in multi-sensor fusion, and distributed sensor networks to develop distributed or consensus Kalman filtering.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The filtering method is named for Hungarian émigré Rudolf E.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Kálmán, although Thorvald Nicolai Thiele and Peter Swerling developed a similar algorithm earlier.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Bucy of the Johns Hopkins Applied Physics Laboratory contributed to the theory, causing it to be known sometimes as Kalman–Bucy filtering.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman was inspired to derive the Kalman filter by applying state variables to the Wiener filtering problem.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Schmidt is generally credited with developing the first implementation of a Kalman filter.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] He realized that the filter could be divided into two distinct parts, with one part for time periods between sensor outputs and another part for incorporating measurements.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] It was during a visit by Kálmán to the NASA Ames Research Center that Schmidt saw the applicability of Kálmán's ideas to the nonlinear problem of trajectory estimation for the Apollo program resulting in its incorporation in the Apollo navigation computer.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This digital filter is sometimes termed the *Stratonovich–Kalman–Bucy filter* because it is a special case of a more general, nonlinear filter developed by the Soviet mathematician Ruslan Stratonovich.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] In fact, some of the special case linear filter's equations appeared in papers by Stratonovich that were published before the summer of 1961, when Kalman met with Stratonovich during a conference in Moscow.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This Kalman filtering was first described and developed partially in technical papers by Swerling (1958), Kalman (1960) and Kalman and Bucy (1961).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filters have been vital in the implementation of the navigation systems of U.S.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Navy nuclear ballistic missile submarines, and in the guidance and navigation systems of cruise missiles such as the U.S.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Air Force's Air Launched Cruise Missile.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] They are also used in the guidance and navigation systems of reusable launch vehicles and the attitude control and navigation systems of spacecraft which dock at the International Space Station.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] As such, it is a common sensor fusion and data fusion algorithm.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Noisy sensor data, approximations in the equations that describe the system evolution, and external factors that are not accounted for, all limit how well it is possible to determine the system's state.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter deals effectively with the uncertainty due to noisy sensor data and, to some extent, with random external factors.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter produces an estimate of the state of the system as an average of the system's predicted state and of the new measurement using a weighted average.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The purpose of the weights is that values with better (i.e., smaller) estimated uncertainty are "trusted" more.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The weights are calculated from the covariance, a measure of the estimated uncertainty of the prediction of the system's state.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The result of the weighted average is a new state estimate that lies between the predicted and measured state, and has a better estimated uncertainty than either alone.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This process is repeated at every time step, with the new estimate and its covariance informing the prediction used in the following iteration.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This means that Kalman filter works recursively and requires only the last "best guess", rather than the entire history, of a system's state to calculate a new state.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The measurements' certainty-grading and current-state estimate are important considerations.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] It is common to discuss the filter's response in terms of the Kalman filter's *gain*.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman gain is the weight given to the measurements and current-state estimate, and can be "tuned" to achieve a particular performance.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] With a high gain, the filter places more weight on the most recent measurements, and thus conforms to them more responsively.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] With a low gain, the filter conforms to the model predictions more closely.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] At the extremes, a high gain (close to one) will result in a more jumpy estimated trajectory, while a low gain (close to zero) will smooth out noise but decrease the responsiveness.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] When performing the actual calculations for the filter (as discussed below), the state estimate and covariances are coded into matrices because of the multiple dimensions involved in a single set of calculations.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This allows for a representation of linear relationships between different state variables (such as position, velocity, and acceleration) in any of the transition models or covariances.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] As an example application, consider the problem of determining the precise location of a truck.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The truck can be equipped with a GPS unit that provides an estimate of the position within a few meters.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The GPS estimate is likely to be noisy; readings 'jump around' rapidly, though remaining within a few meters of the real position.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] In addition, since the truck is expected to follow the laws of physics, its position can also be estimated by integrating its velocity over time, determined by keeping track of wheel revolutions and the angle of the steering wheel.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This is a technique known as dead reckoning.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Typically, the dead reckoning will provide a very smooth estimate of the truck's position, but it will drift over time as small errors accumulate.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] For this example, the Kalman filter can be thought of as operating in two distinct phases: predict and update.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] In the prediction phase, the truck's old position will be modified according to the physical laws of motion (the dynamic or "state transition" model).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Not only will a new position estimate be calculated, but also a new covariance will be calculated as well.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Perhaps the covariance is proportional to the speed of the truck because we are more uncertain about the accuracy of the dead reckoning position estimate at high speeds but very certain about the position estimate at low speeds.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Next, in the update phase, a measurement of the truck's position is taken from the GPS unit.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Along with this measurement comes some amount of uncertainty, and its covariance relative to that of the prediction from the previous phase determines how much the new measurement will affect the updated prediction.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Ideally, as the dead reckoning estimates tend to drift away from the real position, the GPS measurement should pull the position estimate back toward the real position but not disturb it to the point of becoming noisy and rapidly jumping.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter is an efficient recursive filter estimating the internal state of a linear dynamic system from a series of noisy measurements.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] It is used in a wide range of engineering and econometric applications from radar and computer vision to estimation of structural macroeconomic models, and is an important topic in control theory and control systems engineering.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Together with the linear-quadratic regulator (LQR), the Kalman filter solves the linear–quadratic–Gaussian control problem (LQG).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter, the linear-quadratic regulator, and the linear–quadratic–Gaussian controller are solutions to what arguably are the most fundamental problems of control theory.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] In most applications, the internal state is much larger (has more degrees of freedom) than the few "observable" parameters which are measured.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] However, by combining a series of measurements, the Kalman filter can estimate the entire internal state.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] For the Dempster–Shafer theory, each state equation or observation is considered a special case of a linear belief function and the Kalman filtering is a special case of combining linear belief functions on a join-tree or Markov tree.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Additional methods include belief filtering which use Bayes or evidential updates to the state equations.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] A wide variety of Kalman filters exists by now: Kalman's original formulation - now termed the "simple" Kalman filter, the Kalman–Bucy filter, Schmidt's "extended" filter, the information filter, and a variety of "square-root" filters that were developed by Bierman, Thornton, and many others.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Kalman filtering is based on linear dynamic systems discretized in the time domain.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] They are modeled on a Markov chain built on linear operators perturbed by errors that may include Gaussian noise.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The state of the target system refers to the ground truth (yet hidden) system configuration of interest, which is represented as a vector of real numbers.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] At each discrete time increment, a linear operator is applied to the state to generate the new state, with some noise mixed in, and optionally some information from the controls on the system if they are known.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Then, another linear operator mixed with more noise generates the measurable outputs (i.e., observation) from the true ("hidden") state.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter may be regarded as analogous to the hidden Markov model, with the difference that the hidden state variables have values in a continuous space as opposed to a discrete state space as for the hidden Markov model.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] There is a strong analogy between the equations of a Kalman Filter and those of the hidden Markov model.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] A review of this and other models is given in Roweis and Ghahramani (1999) and Hamilton (1994), Chapter 13.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] In order to use the Kalman filter to estimate the internal state of a process given only a sequence of noisy observations, one must model the process in accordance with the following framework.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] As seen below, it is common in many applications that the matrices $\mathbf {F}$ , $\mathbf {H}$ , $\mathbf {Q}$ , $\mathbf {R}$ , and $\mathbf {B}$ are constant across time, in which case their k index may be dropped.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] If $\mathbf {Q}$ is independent of time, one may, following Roweis and Ghahramani, write $\mathbf {w} _{\bullet }$ instead of $\mathbf {w} _{k}$ to emphasize that the noise has no explicit knowledge of time.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Analogously to the situation for $\mathbf {w} _{k}$ , one may write $\mathbf {v} _{\bullet }$ instead of $\mathbf {v} _{k}$ if $\mathbf {R}$ is independent of time.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The initial state, and the noise vectors at each step $\{\mathbf {x} _{0},\mathbf {w} _{1},\dots ,\mathbf {w} _{k},\mathbf {v} _{1},\dots ,\mathbf {v} _{k}\}$ are all assumed to be mutually independent.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Many real-time dynamic systems do not exactly conform to this model.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] In fact, unmodeled dynamics can seriously degrade the filter performance, even when it was supposed to work with unknown stochastic signals as inputs.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The reason for this is that the effect of unmodeled dynamics depends on the input, and, therefore, can bring the estimation algorithm to instability (it diverges).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] On the other hand, independent white noise signals will not make the algorithm diverge.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The problem of distinguishing between measurement noise and unmodeled dynamics is a difficult one and is treated as a problem of control theory using robust control.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter is a recursive estimator.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This means that only the estimated state from the previous time step and the current measurement are needed to compute the estimate for the current state.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] In contrast to batch estimation techniques, no history of observations and/or estimates is required.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] In what follows, the notation ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{n\mid m}$ represents the estimate of $\mathbf {x}$ at time *n* given observations up to and including at time *m* ≤ *n*.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The algorithm structure of the Kalman filter resembles that of Alpha beta filter.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter can be written as a single equation; however, it is most often conceptualized as two distinct phases: "Predict" and "Update".
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The predict phase uses the state estimate from the previous timestep to produce an estimate of the state at the current timestep.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This predicted state estimate is also known as the *a priori* state estimate because, although it is an estimate of the state at the current timestep, it does not include observation information from the current timestep.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] In the update phase, the innovation (the pre-fit residual), i.e. the difference between the current *a priori* prediction and the current observation information, is multiplied by the optimal Kalman gain and combined with the previous state estimate to refine the state estimate.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This improved estimate based on the current observation is termed the *a posteriori* state estimate.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Typically, the two phases alternate, with the prediction advancing the state until the next scheduled observation, and the update incorporating the observation.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] However, this is not necessary; if an observation is unavailable for some reason, the update may be skipped and multiple prediction procedures performed.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Likewise, if multiple independent observations are available at the same time, multiple update procedures may be performed (typically with different observation matrices **H***k*).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The second formula for the updated (*a posteriori*) estimate covariance above is known as the "Joseph form" that is often used in applications (numerically more stable than the more simple usual formulation).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Proof of the formulae is found in the *derivations* section, where the formula valid for any **K**k is also shown.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This expression reminds us of a linear interpolation, $x=(1-t)(a)+t(b)$ for t between [0,1].
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This expression also resembles the alpha beta filter update step.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] where $\operatorname {E} [\xi ]$ is the expected value of $\xi$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] That is, all estimates have a mean error of zero.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] so covariance matrices accurately reflect the covariance of estimates.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Practical implementation of a Kalman Filter is often difficult due to the difficulty of getting a good estimate of the noise covariance matrices **Q***k* and **R***k*.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Extensive research has been done to estimate these covariances from data.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] One practical method of doing this is the *autocovariance least-squares* (ALS) technique that uses the time-lagged autocovariances of routine operating data to estimate the covariances.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The GNU Octave and Matlab code used to calculate the noise covariance matrices using the ALS technique is available online using the GNU General Public License.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Another approach is the *Optimized Kalman Filter* (OKF), which considers the covariance matrices not as representatives of the noise, but rather, as parameters aimed to achieve the most accurate state estimation.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] These two views coincide under the KF assumptions, but often contradict each other in real systems.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Thus, OKF's state estimation is more robust to modeling inaccuracies.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter provides an optimal state estimation in cases where a) the model matches the real system perfectly, b) the entering noise is "white" (uncorrelated), and c) the covariances of the noise are known exactly.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Correlated noise can also be treated using Kalman filters.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Several methods for the noise covariance estimation have been proposed during past decades, including ALS, mentioned in the section above.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] More generally, if the model assumptions do not match the real system perfectly, then optimal state estimation is not necessarily obtained by setting **Q***k* and **R***k* to the covariances of the noise.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Instead, in that case, the parameters **Q***k* and **R***k* may be set to explicitly optimize the state estimation, e.g., using standard supervised learning.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] After the covariances are set, it is useful to evaluate the performance of the filter; i.e., whether it is possible to improve the state estimation quality.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] If the Kalman filter works optimally, the innovation sequence (the output prediction error) is a white noise, therefore the whiteness property of the innovations measures filter performance.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Several different methods can be used for this purpose.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] If the noise terms are distributed in a non-Gaussian manner, methods for assessing performance of the filter estimate, which use probability inequalities or large-sample theory, are known in the literature.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Consider a truck on frictionless, straight rails.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Initially, the truck is stationary at position 0, but it is buffeted this way and that by random uncontrolled forces.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] We measure the position of the truck every Δ*t* seconds, but these measurements are imprecise; we want to maintain a model of the truck's position and velocity.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] We show here how we derive the model from which we create our Kalman filter.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Since $\mathbf {F} ,\mathbf {H} ,\mathbf {R} ,\mathbf {Q}$ are constant, their time indices are dropped.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] where ${\dot {x}}$ is the velocity, that is, the derivative of position with respect to time.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] We assume that between the (*k* − 1) and *k* timestep, uncontrolled forces cause a constant acceleration of *a**k* that is normally distributed with mean 0 and standard deviation *σ**a*.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] (there is no $\mathbf {B} u$ term since there are no known control inputs.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The matrix $\mathbf {Q}$ is not full rank (it is of rank one if $\Delta t\neq 0$ ).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Hence, the distribution $N(0,\mathbf {Q} )$ is not absolutely continuous and has no probability density function.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] At each time phase, a noisy measurement of the true position of the truck is made.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Let us suppose the measurement noise *v**k* is also distributed normally, with mean 0 and standard deviation *σ**z*.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The filter will then prefer the information from the first measurements over the information already in the model.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] For simplicity, assume that the control input $\mathbf {u} _{k}=\mathbf {0}$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] A similar equation holds if we include a non-zero control input.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Gain matrices $\mathbf {K} _{k}$ and covariance matrices $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ evolve independently of the measurements $\mathbf {z} _{k}$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Since these depend only on the model, and not the measurements, they may be computed offline.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Convergence of the gain matrices $\mathbf {K} _{k}$ to an asymptotic matrix $\mathbf {K} _{\infty }$ applies for conditions established in Walrand and Dimakis.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] If the $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ series converges, then it converges exponentially to an asymptotic $\mathbf {P} _{\infty }$ , assuming non-zero plant noise.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Recent analysis has shown that the *rate and nature* of this convergence can involve multiple coequal modes, including oscillatory components, depending on the eigenstructure of the Jacobian of the above Riccati map evaluated at $\mathbf {P} _{\infty }$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] For the moving truck example described above, with $\Delta t=1$ and $\sigma _{a}^{2}=\sigma _{z}^{2}=\sigma _{x}^{2}=\sigma _{\dot {x}}^{2}=1$ , simulation shows convergence in $10$ iterations.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The asymptotic gain is then computed as before.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter can be derived as a generalized least squares method operating on previous data.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This formula (sometimes known as the **Joseph form** of the covariance update equation) is valid for any value of **K***k*.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] It turns out that if **K***k* is the optimal Kalman gain, this can be simplified further as shown below.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter is a minimum mean-square error (MMSE) estimator.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] We seek to minimize the expected value of the square of the magnitude of this vector, $\operatorname {E} \left[\left\|\mathbf {x} _{k}-{\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k|k}\right\|^{2}\right]$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This is equivalent to minimizing the trace of the *a posteriori* estimate covariance matrix $\mathbf {P} _{k|k}$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The trace is minimized when its matrix derivative with respect to the gain matrix is zero.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This gain, which is known as the *optimal Kalman gain*, is the one that yields MMSE estimates when used.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The formula used to calculate the *a posteriori* error covariance can be simplified when the Kalman gain equals the optimal value derived above.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This formula is computationally cheaper and thus nearly always used in practice, but is only correct for the optimal gain.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] If arithmetic precision is unusually low causing problems with numerical stability, or if a non-optimal Kalman gain is deliberately used, this simplification cannot be applied; the *a posteriori* error covariance formula as derived above (Joseph form) must be used.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filtering equations provide an estimate of the state ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid k}$ and its error covariance $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ recursively.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The estimate and its quality depend on the system parameters and the noise statistics fed as inputs to the estimator.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This section analyzes the effect of uncertainties in the statistical inputs to the filter.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] no longer provides the actual error covariance.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] In most real-time applications, the covariance matrices that are used in designing the Kalman filter are different from the actual (true) noise covariances matrices.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This sensitivity analysis describes the behavior of the estimation error covariance when the noise covariances as well as the system matrices $\mathbf {F} _{k}$ and $\mathbf {H} _{k}$ that are fed as inputs to the filter are incorrect.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Thus, the sensitivity analysis describes the robustness (or sensitivity) of the estimator to misspecified statistical and parametric inputs to the estimator.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This discussion is limited to the error sensitivity analysis for the case of statistical uncertainties.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Here the actual noise covariances are denoted by $\mathbf {Q} _{k}^{a}$ and $\mathbf {R} _{k}^{a}$ respectively, whereas the design values used in the estimator are $\mathbf {Q} _{k}$ and $\mathbf {R} _{k}$ respectively.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The actual error covariance is denoted by $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}^{a}$ and $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ as computed by the Kalman filter is referred to as the Riccati variable.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The recursive expressions for $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}^{a}$ and $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ are identical except for the presence of $\mathbf {Q} _{k}^{a}$ and $\mathbf {R} _{k}^{a}$ in place of the design values $\mathbf {Q} _{k}$ and $\mathbf {R} _{k}$ respectively.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Researches have been done to analyze Kalman filter system's robustness.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] One problem with the Kalman filter is its numerical stability.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] If the process noise covariance **Q***k* is small, round-off error often causes a small positive eigenvalue of the state covariance matrix **P** to be computed as a negative number.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This renders the numerical representation of **P** indefinite, while its true form is positive-definite.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Positive definite matrices have the property that they have a factorization into the product of a non-singular, lower-triangular matrix **S** and its transpose : **P** = **S**·**S**T .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The factor **S** can be computed efficiently using the Cholesky factorization algorithm.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This product form of the covariance matrix **P** is guaranteed to be symmetric, and for all 1 <= k <= n, the k-th diagonal element **P**kk is equal to the square of the euclidean norm of the k-th row of **S**, which is necessarily positive.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Between the two, the U-D factorization uses the same amount of storage, and somewhat less computation, and is the most commonly used triangular factorization.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Efficient algorithms for the Kalman prediction and update steps in the factored form were developed by G.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The **L**·**D**·**L**T decomposition of the innovation covariance matrix **S**k is the basis for another type of numerically efficient and robust square root filter.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The algorithm starts with the LU decomposition as implemented in the Linear Algebra PACKage (LAPACK).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] These results are further factored into the **L**·**D**·**L**T structure with methods given by Golub and Van Loan (algorithm 4.1.2) for a symmetric nonsingular matrix.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] Any singular covariance matrix is pivoted so that the first diagonal partition is nonsingular and well-conditioned.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The pivoting algorithm must retain any portion of the innovation covariance matrix directly corresponding to observed state-variables **H**k·**x**k|k-1 that are associated with auxiliary observations in **y**k.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The **l**·**d**·**l**t square-root filter requires orthogonalization of the observation vector.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This may be done with the inverse square-root of the covariance matrix for the auxiliary variables using Method 2 in Higham (2002, p.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The Kalman filter is efficient for sequential data processing on central processing units (CPUs), but in its original form it is inefficient on parallel architectures such as graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] It is however possible to express the filter-update routine in terms of an associative operator using the formulation in Särkkä and García-Fernández (2021).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] The filter solution can then be retrieved by the use of a prefix sum algorithm which can be efficiently implemented on GPU.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p01] This reduces the computational complexity from $O(N)$ in the number of time steps to $O(\log(N))$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The Kalman filter can be presented as one of the simplest dynamic Bayesian networks.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The Kalman filter calculates estimates of the true values of states recursively over time using incoming measurements and a mathematical process model.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Similarly, recursive Bayesian estimation calculates estimates of an unknown probability density function (PDF) recursively over time using incoming measurements and a mathematical process model.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] In recursive Bayesian estimation, the true state is assumed to be an unobserved Markov process, and the measurements are the observed states of a hidden Markov model (HMM).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Because of the Markov assumption, the true state is conditionally independent of all earlier states given the immediately previous state.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Similarly, the measurement at the *k*-th timestep is dependent only upon the current state and is conditionally independent of all other states given the current state.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] However, when a Kalman filter is used to estimate the state **x**, the probability distribution of interest is that associated with the current states conditioned on the measurements up to the current timestep.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] This is achieved by marginalizing out the previous states and dividing by the probability of the measurement set.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] This results in the *predict* and *update* phases of the Kalman filter written probabilistically.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The probability distribution of the update is proportional to the product of the measurement likelihood and the predicted state.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The PDF at the previous timestep is assumed inductively to be the estimated state and covariance.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] This is justified because, as an optimal estimator, the Kalman filter makes best use of the measurements, therefore the PDF for $\mathbf {x} _{k}$ given the measurements $\mathbf {Z} _{k}$ is the Kalman filter estimate.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Related to the recursive Bayesian interpretation described above, the Kalman filter can be viewed as a generative model, i.e., a process for *generating* a stream of random observations **z** = (**z**0, **z**1, **z**2, ...).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] This process has identical structure to the hidden Markov model, except that the discrete state and observations are replaced with continuous variables sampled from Gaussian distributions.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] In some applications, it is useful to compute the *probability* that a Kalman filter with a given set of parameters (prior distribution, transition and observation models, and control inputs) would generate a particular observed signal.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] This probability is known as the marginal likelihood because it integrates over ("marginalizes out") the values of the hidden state variables, so it can be computed using only the observed signal.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The marginal likelihood can be useful to evaluate different parameter choices, or to compare the Kalman filter against other models using Bayesian model comparison.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] It is straightforward to compute the marginal likelihood as a side effect of the recursive filtering computation.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] i.e., a product of Gaussian densities, each corresponding to the density of one observation **z***k* under the current filtering distribution $\mathbf {H} _{k}{\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid k-1},\mathbf {S} _{k}$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] This can easily be computed as a simple recursive update; however, to avoid numeric underflow, in a practical implementation it is usually desirable to compute the *log* marginal likelihood $\ell =\log p(\mathbf {z} )$ instead.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] where $d_{y}$ is the dimension of the measurement vector.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] An important application where such a (log) likelihood of the observations (given the filter parameters) is used is multi-target tracking.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] For example, consider an object tracking scenario where a stream of observations is the input, however, it is unknown how many objects are in the scene (or, the number of objects is known but is greater than one).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] For such a scenario, it can be unknown apriori which observations/measurements were generated by which object.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] A multiple hypothesis tracker (MHT) typically will form different track association hypotheses, where each hypothesis can be considered as a Kalman filter (for the linear Gaussian case) with a specific set of parameters associated with the hypothesized object.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Thus, it is important to compute the likelihood of the observations for the different hypotheses under consideration, such that the most-likely one can be found.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Additionally, the information filter allows for system information initialization according to ${I_{1|0}=P_{1|0}^{-1}=0}$ , which would not be possible for the regular Kalman filter.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] In the information filter, or inverse covariance filter, the estimated covariance and estimated state are replaced by the information matrix and information vector respectively.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The information update now becomes a trivial sum.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The main advantage of the information filter is that *N* measurements can be filtered at each time step simply by summing their information matrices and vectors.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] To predict the information filter the information matrix and vector can be converted back to their state space equivalents, or alternatively the information space prediction can be used.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The optimal fixed-lag smoother provides the optimal estimate of ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k-N\mid k}$ for a given fixed-lag N using the measurements from $\mathbf {z} _{1}$ to $\mathbf {z} _{k}$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The optimal fixed-interval smoother provides the optimal estimate of ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid n}$ ( $k<n$ ) using the measurements from a fixed interval $\mathbf {z} _{1}$ to $\mathbf {z} _{n}$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] There are several smoothing algorithms in common use.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The Rauch–Tung–Striebel (RTS) smoother is an efficient two-pass algorithm for fixed interval smoothing.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The forward pass is the same as the regular Kalman filter algorithm.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] These *filtered* a-priori and a-posteriori state estimates ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid k-1}$ , ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid k}$ and covariances $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k-1}$ , $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid k}$ are saved for use in the backward pass (for retrodiction).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] In the backward pass, we compute the *smoothed* state estimates ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k\mid n}$ and covariances $\mathbf {P} _{k\mid n}$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] $\mathbf {x} _{k\mid k}$ is the a-posteriori state estimate of timestep k and $\mathbf {x} _{k+1\mid k}$ is the a-priori state estimate of timestep $k+1$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The same notation applies to the covariance.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] An alternative to the RTS algorithm is the modified Bryson–Frazier (MBF) fixed interval smoother developed by Bierman.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] This also uses a backward pass that processes data saved from the Kalman filter forward pass.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The equations for the backward pass involve the recursive computation of data which are used at each observation time to compute the smoothed state and covariance.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] An important advantage of the MBF is that it does not require finding the inverse of the covariance matrix.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Bierman's derivation is based on the RTS smoother, which assumes that the underlying distributions are Gaussian.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] However, a derivation of the MBF based on the concept of the fixed point smoother, which does not require the Gaussian assumption, is given by Gibbs.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The MBF can also be used to perform consistency checks on the filter residuals and the difference between the value of a filter state after an update and the smoothed value of the state, that is $\mathbf {x} _{k\mid k}-\mathbf {x} _{k\mid n}$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The minimum-variance smoother can attain the best-possible error performance, provided that the models are linear, their parameters and the noise statistics are known precisely.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] This smoother is a time-varying state-space generalization of the optimal non-causal Wiener filter.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The smoother calculations are done in two passes.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The above system is known as the inverse Wiener-Hopf factor.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The backward recursion is the adjoint of the above forward system.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The result of the backward pass $\beta _{k}$ may be calculated by operating the forward equations on the time-reversed $\alpha _{k}$ and time reversing the result.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] which is identical to the minimum-variance Kalman filter.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The above solutions minimize the variance of the output estimation error.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Note that the Rauch–Tung–Striebel smoother derivation assumes that the underlying distributions are Gaussian, whereas the minimum-variance solutions do not.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Optimal smoothers for state estimation and input estimation can be constructed similarly.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] A continuous-time version of the above smoother is described in.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Expectation–maximization algorithms may be employed to calculate approximate maximum likelihood estimates of unknown state-space parameters within minimum-variance filters and smoothers.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Often uncertainties remain within problem assumptions.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] A smoother that accommodates uncertainties can be designed by adding a positive definite term to the Riccati equation.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] In cases where the models are nonlinear, step-wise linearizations may be within the minimum-variance filter and smoother recursions (extended Kalman filtering).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Pioneering research on the perception of sounds at different frequencies was conducted by Fletcher and Munson in the 1930s.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Their work led to a standard way of weighting measured sound levels within investigations of industrial noise and hearing loss.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Frequency weightings have since been used within filter and controller designs to manage performance within bands of interest.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Typically, a frequency shaping function is used to weight the average power of the error spectral density in a specified frequency band.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Let $\mathbf {y} -{\hat {\mathbf {y} }}$ denote the output estimation error exhibited by a conventional Kalman filter.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Also, let $\mathbf {W}$ denote a causal frequency weighting transfer function.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The optimum solution which minimizes the variance of $\mathbf {W} \left(\mathbf {y} -{\hat {\mathbf {y} }}\right)$ arises by simply constructing $\mathbf {W} ^{-1}{\hat {\mathbf {y} }}$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The design of $\mathbf {W}$ remains an open question.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] One way of proceeding is to identify a system which generates the estimation error and setting $\mathbf {W}$ equal to the inverse of that system.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] This procedure may be iterated to obtain mean-square error improvement at the cost of increased filter order.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The same technique can be applied to smoothers.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The basic Kalman filter is limited to a linear assumption.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] More complex systems, however, can be nonlinear.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The nonlinearity can be associated either with the process model or with the observation model or with both.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The most common variants of Kalman filters for non-linear systems are the Extended Kalman Filter and Unscented Kalman filter.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The suitability of which filter to use depends on the non-linearity indices of the process and observation model.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] In the extended Kalman filter (EKF), the state transition and observation models need not be linear functions of the state but may instead be nonlinear functions.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] These functions are of differentiable type.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The function *f* can be used to compute the predicted state from the previous estimate and similarly the function *h* can be used to compute the predicted measurement from the predicted state.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] However, *f* and *h* cannot be applied to the covariance directly.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Instead a matrix of partial derivatives (the Jacobian) is computed.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] At each timestep the Jacobian is evaluated with current predicted states.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] These matrices can be used in the Kalman filter equations.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] This process essentially linearizes the nonlinear function around the current estimate.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] When the state transition and observation models—that is, the predict and update functions f and h —are highly nonlinear, the extended Kalman filter can give particularly poor performance.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] This is because the covariance is propagated through linearization of the underlying nonlinear model.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The unscented Kalman filter (UKF) uses a deterministic sampling technique known as the unscented transformation (UT) to pick a minimal set of sample points (called sigma points) around the mean.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The sigma points are then propagated through the nonlinear functions, from which a new mean and covariance estimate are formed.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The resulting filter depends on how the transformed statistics of the UT are calculated and which set of sigma points are used.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] It should be remarked that it is always possible to construct new UKFs in a consistent way.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] For certain systems, the resulting UKF more accurately estimates the true mean and covariance.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] This can be verified with Monte Carlo sampling or Taylor series expansion of the posterior statistics.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Typically, $\mathbf {A}$ is obtained via Cholesky decomposition of $\mathbf {P} _{k-1\mid k-1}$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] With some care the filter equations can be expressed in such a way that $\mathbf {A}$ is evaluated directly without intermediate calculations of $\mathbf {P} _{k-1\mid k-1}$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] This is referred to as the *square-root unscented Kalman filter*.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The weight of the mean value, $W_{0}$ , can be chosen arbitrarily.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] $\alpha$ and $\kappa$ control the spread of the sigma points. $\beta$ is related to the distribution of x .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Note that this is an overparameterization in the sense that any one of $\alpha$ , $\beta$ and $\kappa$ can be chosen arbitrarily.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Appropriate values depend on the problem at hand, but a typical recommendation is $\alpha =1$ , $\beta =0$ , and $\kappa \approx 3L/2$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] If the true distribution of x is Gaussian, $\beta =2$ is optimal.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] As with the EKF, the UKF prediction can be used independently from the UKF update, in combination with a linear (or indeed EKF) update, or vice versa.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Given estimates of the mean and covariance, ${\hat {\mathbf {x} }}_{k-1\mid k-1}$ and $\mathbf {P} _{k-1\mid k-1}$ , one obtains $N=2L+1$ sigma points as described in the section above.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The sigma points are propagated through the transition function *f*.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The propagated sigma points are weighed to produce the predicted mean and covariance.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] where $W_{j}^{a}$ are the first-order weights of the original sigma points, and $W_{j}^{c}$ are the second-order weights.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The matrix $\mathbf {Q} _{k}$ is the covariance of the transition noise, $\mathbf {w} _{k}$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] These sigma points are transformed through the measurement function h .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Then the empirical mean and covariance of the transformed points are calculated.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] where $\mathbf {R} _{k}$ is the covariance matrix of the observation noise, $\mathbf {v} _{k}$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] This replaces the generative specification of the standard Kalman filter with a discriminative model for the latent states given observations.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Such an approach proves particularly useful when the dimensionality of the observations is much greater than that of the latent states and can be used to build filters that are particularly robust to nonstationarities in the observation model.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Adaptive Kalman filters allow to adapt for process dynamics which are not modeled in the process model $\mathbf {F} (t)$ , which happens for example in the context of a maneuvering target when a constant velocity (reduced order) Kalman filter is employed for tracking.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Kalman–Bucy filtering (named for Richard Snowden Bucy) is a continuous time version of Kalman filtering.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] where $\mathbf {Q} (t)$ and $\mathbf {R} (t)$ represent the intensities of the two white noise terms $\mathbf {w} (t)$ and $\mathbf {v} (t)$ , respectively.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The distinction between the prediction and update steps of discrete-time Kalman filtering does not exist in continuous time.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The second differential equation, for the covariance, is an example of a Riccati equation.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Nonlinear generalizations to Kalman–Bucy filters include continuous time extended Kalman filter.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Most physical systems are represented as continuous-time models while discrete-time measurements are made frequently for state estimation via a digital processor.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The prediction equations are derived from those of continuous-time Kalman filter without update from measurements, i.e., $\mathbf {K} (t)=0$ .
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The predicted state and covariance are calculated respectively by solving a set of differential equations with the initial value equal to the estimate at the previous step.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] For the case of linear time invariant systems, the continuous time dynamics can be exactly discretized into a discrete time system using matrix exponentials.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The update equations are identical to those of the discrete-time Kalman filter.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] The traditional Kalman filter has also been employed for the recovery of sparse, possibly dynamic, signals from noisy observations.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Recent works utilize notions from the theory of compressed sensing/sampling, such as the restricted isometry property and related probabilistic recovery arguments, for sequentially estimating the sparse state in intrinsically low-dimensional systems.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/kalman-filter-p02] Since linear Gaussian state-space models lead to Gaussian processes, Kalman filters can be viewed as sequential solvers for Gaussian process regression.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] A **reaction control system** (**RCS**) is a spacecraft system that uses thrusters to provide attitude control and translation.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] Alternatively, reaction wheels can be used for attitude control, rather than RCS.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] Use of diverted engine thrust to provide stable attitude control of a short-or-vertical takeoff and landing aircraft below conventional winged flight speeds, such as with the Harrier "jump jet", may also be referred to as a reaction control system.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] Reaction control systems are capable of providing small amounts of thrust in any desired direction or combination of directions.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] An RCS is also capable of providing torque to allow control of rotation (roll, pitch, and yaw).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] Reaction control systems often use combinations of large and small (vernier) thrusters, to allow different levels of response.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] Because spacecraft only contain a finite amount of fuel and there is little chance to refill them, alternative reaction control systems have been developed so that fuel can be conserved.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] For stationkeeping, some spacecraft (particularly those in geosynchronous orbit) use high-specific impulse engines such as arcjets, ion thrusters, or Hall effect thrusters.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] To control orientation, a few spacecraft, including the ISS, use momentum wheels which spin to control rotational rates on the vehicle.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] The Mercury space capsule and Gemini reentry module both used groupings of nozzles to provide attitude control.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] The thrusters were located off their center of mass, thus providing a torque to rotate the capsule.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] The Gemini capsule was also capable of adjusting its reentry course by rolling, which directed its off-center lifting force.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] The Mercury thrusters used a hydrogen peroxide monopropellant which turned to steam when forced through a tungsten screen, and the Gemini thrusters used hypergolic mono-methyl hydrazine fuel oxidized with nitrogen tetroxide.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] The Gemini spacecraft was also equipped with a hypergolic Orbit Attitude and Maneuvering System, which made it the first crewed spacecraft with translation as well as rotation capability.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] In-orbit attitude control was achieved by firing pairs of eight 25-pound-force (110 N) thrusters located around the circumference of its adapter module at the extreme aft end.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] Lateral translation control was provided by four 100-pound-force (440 N) thrusters around the circumference at the forward end of the adaptor module (close to the spacecraft's center of mass).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] Two forward-pointing 85-pound-force (380 N) thrusters at the same location, provided aft translation, and two 100-pound-force (440 N) thrusters located in the aft end of the adapter module provided forward thrust, which could be used to change the craft's orbit.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] The Gemini reentry module also had a separate Reentry Control System of sixteen thrusters located at the base of its nose, to provide rotational control during reentry.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] The Apollo Command Module had a set of twelve hypergolic thrusters for attitude control, and directional reentry control similar to Gemini.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] The Apollo Service Module and Lunar Module each had a set of sixteen R-4D hypergolic thrusters, grouped into external clusters of four, to provide both translation and attitude control.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] The clusters were located near the craft's average centers of mass, and were fired in pairs in opposite directions for attitude control.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] A pair of translation thrusters are located at the rear of the Soyuz spacecraft; the counter-acting thrusters are similarly paired in the middle of the spacecraft (near the center of mass) pointing outwards and forward.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] These act in pairs to prevent the spacecraft from rotating.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] The thrusters for the lateral directions are mounted close to the center of mass of the spacecraft, in pairs as well.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] Those for pitch and yaw are located in the nose, forward of the cockpit, and replace a standard radar system.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] Those for roll are located at the wingtips.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] The X-20, which would have gone into orbit, continued this pattern.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] Unlike these, the Space Shuttle Orbiter had many more thrusters, which were required to control vehicle attitude in both orbital flight and during the early part of atmospheric entry, as well as carry out rendezvous and docking maneuvers in orbit.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] Shuttle thrusters were grouped in the nose of the vehicle and on each of the two aft Orbital Maneuvering System pods.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] No nozzles interrupted the heat shield on the underside of the craft; instead, the nose RCS nozzles which control positive pitch were mounted on the side of the vehicle, and were canted downward.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] The downward-facing negative pitch thrusters were located in the OMS pods mounted in the tail/afterbody.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/reaction-control-system] The International Space Station uses electrically powered control moment gyroscopes (CMG) for primary attitude control, with RCS thruster systems as backup and augmentation systems.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Controlling vehicle attitude requires actuators to apply the torques needed to orient the vehicle to a desired attitude, and algorithms to command the actuators based on the current attitude and specification of a desired attitude.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Before and during attitude control can be performed, **spacecraft attitude determination** must be performed, which requires sensors for absolute or relative measurement.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The broader integrated field that studies the combination of sensors, actuators and algorithms is called *guidance, navigation and control*, which also involves non-attitude concepts, such as position determination and navigation.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Spacecraft generally have an attitude determination and control system (ADCS), which includes both sensors and actuators.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] However, budget satellites (such as some cubesats), may elect for simpler attitude control systems (ACS) which use passive techniques, including the yo-yo de-spin technique and permanent magnets to control the attitude of the satellite.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] A spacecraft's attitude must typically be stabilized and controlled for a variety of reasons.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Many spacecraft have components that require articulation or pointing.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Voyager and *Galileo*, for example, were designed with scan platforms for pointing optical instruments at their targets largely independently of spacecraft orientation.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Many spacecraft, such as Mars orbiters, have solar panels that must track the Sun so they can provide electrical power to the spacecraft.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] *Cassini*'s main engine nozzles were steerable.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Knowing where to point a solar panel, or scan platform, or a nozzle — that is, how to articulate it — requires knowledge of the spacecraft's attitude.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Because a single subsystem keeps track of the spacecraft's attitude, the Sun's location, and Earth's location, it can compute the proper direction to point the appendages.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] It logically falls to the same subsystem – the Attitude and Articulation Control Subsystem (AACS), then, to manage both attitude and articulation.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The name AACS may even be carried over to a spacecraft even if it has no appendages to articulate.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Attitude is part of the description of how an object is placed in the space it occupies.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Attitude and position fully describe how an object is placed in space.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] For some applications (e.g., robotics, computer vision), it is customary to combine position and attitude together into a single description known as Pose.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Attitude can be described using a variety of methods; however, the most common are Rotation matrices, Quaternions, and Euler angles.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] While Euler angles are oftentimes the most straightforward representation to visualize, they can cause problems for highly-maneuverable systems because of a phenomenon known as Gimbal lock.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] A rotation matrix, on the other hand, provides a full description of the attitude at the expense of requiring nine values instead of three.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The use of a rotation matrix can lead to increased computational expense and they can be more difficult to work with.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Quaternions offer a decent compromise in that they do not suffer from gimbal lock and only require four values to fully describe the attitude.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Attitude control of spacecraft is maintained using one of two principal approaches: spin stabilization and three-axis stabilization.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Spin stabilization is accomplished by setting the spacecraft spinning, using the gyroscopic action of the rotating spacecraft mass as the stabilizing mechanism.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Propulsion system thrusters are fired only occasionally to make desired changes in spin rate, or in the spin-stabilized attitude.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] If desired, the spinning may be stopped through the use of thrusters or by yo-yo de-spin.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The *Pioneer 10* and *Pioneer 11* probes in the outer Solar System are examples of spin-stabilized spacecraft.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Three-axis stabilization is an alternative method of spacecraft attitude control in which the spacecraft is held fixed in the desired orientation without any rotation.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] There are advantages and disadvantages to both spin stabilization and three-axis stabilization.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Three-axis controlled craft can point optical instruments and antennas without having to de-spin them, but they may have to carry out special rotating maneuvers to best utilize their fields and particle instruments.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] If thrusters are used for routine stabilization, optical observations such as imaging must be designed knowing that the spacecraft is always slowly rocking back and forth, and not always exactly predictably.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Vernier thrusters are the most common actuators, as they may be used for station keeping as well.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Thrusters must be organized as a system to provide stabilization about all three axes, and at least two thrusters are generally used in each axis to provide torque as a couple in order to prevent imparting a translation to the vehicle.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Their limitations are fuel usage, engine wear, and cycles of the control valves.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The fuel efficiency of an attitude control system is determined by its specific impulse (proportional to exhaust velocity) and the smallest torque impulse it can provide (which determines how often the thrusters must fire to provide precise control).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Thrusters must be fired in one direction to start rotation, and again in the opposing direction if a new orientation is to be held.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Thruster systems have been used on most crewed space vehicles, including Vostok, Mercury, Gemini, Apollo, Soyuz, and the Space Shuttle.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] To minimize the fuel limitation on mission duration, auxiliary attitude control systems may be used to reduce vehicle rotation to lower levels, such as small ion thrusters that accelerate ionized gases electrically to extreme velocities, using power from solar cells.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Momentum wheels are electric motor driven rotors made to spin in the direction opposite to that required to re-orient the vehicle.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Because momentum wheels make up a small fraction of the spacecraft's mass and are computer controlled, they give precise control.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Momentum wheels are generally suspended on magnetic bearings to avoid bearing friction and breakdown problems.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Spacecraft Reaction wheels often use mechanical ball bearings.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] To maintain orientation in three dimensional space a minimum of three reaction wheels must be used, with additional units providing single failure protection.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] These are rotors spun at constant speed, mounted on gimbals to provide attitude control.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Although a CMG provides control about the two axes orthogonal to the gyro spin axis, triaxial control still requires two units.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] A CMG is a bit more expensive in terms of cost and mass, because gimbals and their drive motors must be provided.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The maximum torque (but not the maximum angular momentum change) exerted by a CMG is greater than for a momentum wheel, making it better suited to large spacecraft.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] A major drawback is the additional complexity, which increases the number of failure points.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] For this reason, the International Space Station uses a set of four CMGs to provide dual failure tolerance.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Small solar sails (devices that produce thrust as a reaction force induced by reflecting incident light) may be used to make small attitude control and velocity adjustments.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] This application can save large amounts of fuel on a long-duration mission by producing control moments without fuel expenditure.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] For example, *Mariner 10* adjusted its attitude using its solar cells and antennas as small solar sails.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] In orbit, a spacecraft with one axis much longer than the other two will spontaneously orient so that its long axis points at the planet's center of mass.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] This system has the virtue of needing no active control system or expenditure of fuel.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The upper end of the vehicle feels less gravitational pull than the lower end.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] This provides a restoring torque whenever the long axis is not co-linear with the direction of gravity.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Unless some means of damping is provided, the spacecraft will oscillate about the local vertical.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Sometimes tethers are used to connect two parts of a satellite, to increase the stabilizing torque.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] A problem with such tethers is that meteoroids as small as a grain of sand can part them.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Coils or (on very small satellites) permanent magnets exert a moment against the local magnetic field.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] This method works only where there is a magnetic field against which to react.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] One classic field "coil" is actually in the form of a conductive tether in a planetary magnetic field.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Such a conductive tether can also generate electrical power, at the expense of orbital decay.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Conversely, by inducing a counter-current, using solar cell power, the orbit may be raised.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Due to massive variability in Earth's magnetic field from an ideal radial field, control laws based on torques coupling to this field will be highly non-linear.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Moreover, only two-axis control is available at any given time meaning that a vehicle reorient may be necessary to null all rates.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Three main types of passive attitude control exist for satellites.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The first one uses gravity gradient, and it leads to four stable states with the long axis (axis with smallest moment of inertia) pointing towards Earth.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] As this system has four stable states, if the satellite has a preferred orientation, e.g. a camera pointed at the planet, some way to flip the satellite and its tether end-for-end is needed.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The second passive system orients the satellite along Earth's magnetic field thanks to a magnet.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] These purely passive attitude control systems have limited pointing accuracy, because the spacecraft will oscillate around energy minima.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] This drawback is overcome by adding damper, which can be hysteretic materials or a viscous damper.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The viscous damper is a small can or tank of fluid mounted in the spacecraft, possibly with internal baffles to increase internal friction.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Friction within the damper will gradually convert oscillation energy into heat dissipated within the viscous damper.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] A third form of passive attitude control is aerodynamic stabilization.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] This is achieved using a drag gradient, as demonstrated on the Get Away Special Passive Attitude Control Satellite (GASPACS) technology demonstration.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] In low Earth orbit, the force due to drag is many orders of magnitude more dominant than the force imparted due to gravity gradients.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] When a satellite is utilizing aerodynamic passive attitude control, air molecules from the Earth's upper atmosphere strike the satellite in such a way that the center of pressure remains behind the center of mass, similar to how the feathers on an arrow stabilize the arrow.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] GASPACS utilized a 1 m inflatable 'AeroBoom', which extended behind the satellite, creating a stabilizing torque along the satellite's velocity vector.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Another form of passive attitude control is yo-yo de-spin.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Yo-yo de-spin devices are controversial as they generate space debris, and are primarily used for deep-space spacecraft.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Control algorithms are computer programs that receive data from vehicle sensors and derive the appropriate commands to the actuators to rotate the vehicle to the desired attitude.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The algorithms range from very simple, e.g. proportional control, to complex nonlinear estimators or many in-between types, depending on mission requirements.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Typically, the attitude control algorithms are part of the software running on the computer hardware, which receives commands from the ground and formats vehicle data telemetry for transmission to a ground station.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The attitude control algorithms are written and implemented based on requirement for a particular attitude maneuver.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Asides the implementation of passive attitude control such as the gravity-gradient stabilization, most spacecraft make use of active control which exhibits a typical attitude control loop.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The design of the control algorithm depends on the actuator to be used for the specific attitude maneuver although using a simple *proportional–integral–derivative controller* (*PID controller*) satisfies most control needs.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The appropriate commands to the actuators are obtained based on error signals described as the difference between the measured and desired attitude.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The error signals are commonly measured as euler angles (Φ, θ, Ψ), however an alternative to this could be described in terms of direction cosine matrix or error quaternions.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] where $T_{c}$ is the control torque, e is the attitude deviation signal, and $K_{\text{p}},K_{\text{i}},K_{\text{d}}$ are the PID controller parameters.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] A simple implementation of this can be the application of the proportional control for nadir pointing making use of either momentum or reaction wheels as actuators.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] This control algorithm also affects momentum dumping.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Another important and common control algorithm involves the concept of detumbling, which is attenuating the angular momentum of the spacecraft.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The need to detumble the spacecraft arises from the uncontrollable state after release from the launch vehicle.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Most spacecraft in low Earth orbit (LEO) makes use of magnetic detumbling concept which utilizes the effect of the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The control algorithm is called the B-Dot controller and relies on magnetic coils or torque rods as control actuators.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The control law is based on the measurement of the rate of change of body-fixed magnetometer signals.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] where m is the commanded magnetic dipole moment of the magnetic torquer and K is the proportional gain and ${\dot {B}}$ is the rate of change of the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] A spacecraft's ADCS system generally begins detumbling at the start of the mission, either autonomously or when commanded.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Nadir pointing mode and sun pointing mode, among others, are implemented by using actuators to put the spacecraft into a Y-Thomson spin, named after William T.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Thomson, whereby the spacecraft completes one full rotation about its orbit normal axis as it completes one full revolution about the primary body.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] In a geocentric satellite, a Y-Thomson spin is often used to point one face of the spacecraft to face the center of gravity of the Earth.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] This spin aligns the spacecraft body frame with the orbit's tangent-normal-radial reference frame.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] When combined with a nadir-pointing deployable boom, gravity-gradient forces passively stabilize the spacecraft's attitude.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Many sensors generate outputs that reflect the rate of change in attitude.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] These require a known initial attitude, or external information to use them to determine attitude.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Many of this class of sensor have some noise, leading to inaccuracies if not corrected by absolute attitude sensors.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Gyroscopes are devices that sense rotation in three-dimensional space without reliance on the observation of external objects.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Classically, a gyroscope consists of a spinning mass, but there are also "ring laser gyros" utilizing coherent light reflected around a closed path.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Another type of "gyro" is a hemispherical resonator gyro where a crystal cup shaped like a wine glass can be driven into oscillation just as a wine glass "sings" as a finger is rubbed around its rim.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] The orientation of the oscillation is fixed in inertial space, so measuring the orientation of the oscillation relative to the spacecraft can be used to sense the motion of the spacecraft with respect to inertial space.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Motion reference units are a kind of inertial measurement unit with single- or multi-axis motion sensors.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Some multi-axis MRUs are capable of measuring roll, pitch, yaw and heave.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] This class of sensors sense the position or orientation of fields, objects or other phenomena outside the spacecraft.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] A *horizon sensor* is an optical instrument that detects light from the 'limb' of Earth's atmosphere, i.e., at the horizon.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Thermal infrared sensing is often used, which senses the comparative warmth of the atmosphere, compared to the much colder cosmic background.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] This sensor provides orientation with respect to Earth about two orthogonal axes.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] It tends to be less precise than sensors based on stellar observation.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Sometimes referred to as an Earth sensor.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Thus, the horizon sensor provides pitch and roll measurements, and the gyro provides yaw.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] A *Sun sensor* is a device that senses the direction to the Sun.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] This can be as simple as some solar cells and shades, or as complex as a steerable telescope, depending on mission requirements.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] An *Earth sensor* is a device that senses the direction to Earth.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] It is usually an infrared camera; nowadays the main method to detect attitude is the star tracker, but Earth sensors are still integrated in satellites for their low cost and reliability.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] A *star tracker* is an optical device that measures the position(s) of star(s) using photocell(s) or a camera.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] It uses magnitude of brightness and spectral type to identify and then calculate the relative position of stars around it.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] A *magnetometer* is a device that senses magnetic field strength and, when used in a three-axis triad, magnetic field direction.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] As a spacecraft navigational aid, sensed field strength and direction is compared to a map of Earth's magnetic field stored in the memory of an on-board or ground-based guidance computer.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] If spacecraft position is known then attitude can be inferred.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Attitude cannot be measured directly by any single measurement, and so must be calculated (or estimated) from a set of measurements (often using different sensors).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Static attitude estimation methods are solutions to Wahba's problem.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Many solutions have been proposed, notably Davenport's q-method, QUEST, TRIAD, and singular value decomposition.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Kalman filtering can be used to sequentially estimate the attitude, as well as the angular rate.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Because attitude dynamics (combination of rigid body dynamics and attitude kinematics) are non-linear, a linear Kalman filter is not sufficient.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Because attitude dynamics is not very non-linear, the Extended Kalman filter is usually sufficient (however Crassidis and Markely demonstrated that the Unscented Kalman filter could be used, and can provide benefits in cases where the initial estimate is poor).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] Multiple methods have been proposed, however the Multiplicative Extended Kalman Filter (MEKF) is by far the most common approach.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] This approach utilizes the multiplicative formulation of the error quaternion, which allows for the unity constraint on the quaternion to be better handled.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] It is also common to use a technique known as dynamic model replacement, where the angular rate is not estimated directly, but rather the measured angular rate from the gyro is used directly to propagate the rotational dynamics forward in time.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] This is valid for most applications as gyros are typically far more precise than one's knowledge of disturbance torques acting on the system (which is required for precise estimation of the angular rate).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] For some sensors and applications (such as spacecraft using magnetometers) the precise location must also be known.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] While pose estimation can be employed, for spacecraft it is usually sufficient to estimate the position (via Orbit determination) separate from the attitude estimation.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] For terrestrial vehicles and spacecraft operating near the Earth, the advent of Satellite navigation systems allows for precise position knowledge to be obtained easily.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft-attitude-control] This problem becomes more complicated for deep space vehicles, or terrestrial vehicles operating in Global Navigation Satellite System (GNSS) denied environments (see Navigation).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] A **spacecraft** is a vehicle that is designed to fly and operate in outer space.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Spacecraft are used for a variety of purposes, including communications, Earth observation, meteorology, navigation, space colonization, planetary exploration, and transportation of humans and cargo.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] All spacecraft except single-stage-to-orbit vehicles cannot get into space on their own, and require a launch vehicle (carrier rocket).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] On a sub-orbital spaceflight, a space vehicle enters space and then returns to the surface without having gained sufficient energy or velocity to make a full Earth orbit.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] For orbital spaceflights, spacecraft enter closed orbits around the Earth or around other celestial bodies.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Spacecraft used for human spaceflight carry people on board as crew or passengers from start or on orbit (space stations) only, whereas those used for robotic space missions operate either autonomously or telerobotically.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Robotic spacecraft used to support scientific research are space probes.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Robotic spacecraft that remain in orbit around a planetary body are artificial satellites.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] To date, only a handful of interstellar probes, such as *Pioneer 10* and *11*, *Voyager 1* and *2*, and *New Horizons,* are on trajectories that leave the Solar System.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Orbital spacecraft may be recoverable or not.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Recoverable spacecraft may be subdivided by a method of reentry to Earth into non-winged space capsules and winged spaceplanes.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Recoverable spacecraft may be reusable (can be launched again or several times, like the SpaceX Dragon and the Space Shuttle orbiters) or expendable (like the Soyuz).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] In recent years, more space agencies are tending towards reusable spacecraft.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Humanity has achieved space flight, but only a few nations have the technology for orbital launches: Russia (Roscosmos), the United States (NASA), the member states of the European Space Agency, Japan (JAXA), China (CNSA), India (ISRO), Israel (ISA), Iran (ISA), and North Korea (NATA).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] In addition, several private companies have developed or are developing the technology for orbital launches independently from government agencies.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Two prominent examples of such companies are SpaceX and Blue Origin.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] A German V-2, co-designed by Wernher von Braun, became the first spacecraft when it reached an altitude of 189 km in June 1944 in Peenemünde, Germany.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Sputnik 1 was the first artificial satellite.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] It was launched into an elliptical low Earth orbit (LEO) by the Soviet Union on 4 October 1957.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The launch ushered in new political, military, technological, and scientific developments; while the Sputnik launch was a single event, it marked the start of the Space Age.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Apart from its value as a technological first, Sputnik 1 also helped to identify the upper atmospheric layer's density, by measuring the satellite's orbital changes.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] It also provided data on radio-signal distribution in the ionosphere.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Pressurized nitrogen in the satellite's false body provided the first opportunity for meteoroid detection.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Sputnik 1 was launched during the International Geophysical Year from Site No.1/5, at the 5th Tyuratam range, in Kazakh SSR (now at the Baikonur Cosmodrome).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] While Sputnik 1 was the first spacecraft to orbit the Earth, other human-made objects had previously reached an altitude of 100 km, which is the height required by the international organization Fédération Aéronautique Internationale to count as a spaceflight.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] This altitude is called the Kármán line.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] In particular, in the 1940s there were several test launches of the V-2 rocket, some of which reached altitudes well over 100 km.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] As of 2016, only three nations have flown crewed spacecraft: USSR/Russia, USA, and China.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The first crewed spacecraft was Vostok 1, which carried Soviet cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin into space in 1961, and completed a full Earth orbit.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] There were five other crewed missions which used a Vostok spacecraft.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The second crewed spacecraft was named *Freedom 7*, and it performed a sub-orbital spaceflight in 1961 carrying American astronaut Alan Shepard to an altitude of just over 187 kilometers (116 mi).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] There were five other crewed missions using Mercury spacecraft.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Other Soviet crewed spacecraft include the Voskhod, Soyuz, flown uncrewed as Zond/L1, L3, TKS, and the Salyut and *Mir* crewed space stations.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] US company Boeing also developed and flown a spacecraft of their own, the CST-100, commonly referred to as Starliner, but a crewed flight is yet to occur.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] China developed, but did not fly Shuguang, and is currently using Shenzhou (its first crewed mission was in 2003).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Except for the Space Shuttle and the Buran spaceplane of the Soviet Union, the latter of which only ever had one uncrewed test flight, all of the recoverable crewed orbital spacecraft were space capsules.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The International Space Station, crewed since November 2000, is a joint venture between Russia, the United States, Canada and several other countries.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Uncrewed spacecraft are spacecraft without people on board.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Uncrewed spacecraft may have varying levels of autonomy from human input; they may be remote controlled, remote guided or even autonomous, meaning they have a pre-programmed list of operations, which they will execute unless otherwise instructed.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Many space missions are more suited to telerobotic rather than crewed operation, due to lower cost and lower risk factors.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] In addition, some planetary destinations such as Venus or the vicinity of Jupiter are too hostile for human survival.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Outer planets such as Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune are too distant to reach with current crewed spaceflight technology, so telerobotic probes are the only way to explore them.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Telerobotics also allows exploration of regions that are vulnerable to contamination by Earth micro-organisms since spacecraft can be sterilized.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Humans can not be sterilized in the same way as a spaceship, as they coexist with numerous micro-organisms, and these micro-organisms are also hard to contain within a spaceship or spacesuit.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Multiple space probes were sent to study Moon, the planets, the Sun, multiple small Solar System bodies (comets and asteroids).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Special class of uncrewed spacecraft is space telescopes, a telescope in outer space used to observe astronomical objects.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The first operational telescopes were the American Orbiting Astronomical Observatory, OAO-2 launched in 1968, and the Soviet Orion 1 ultraviolet telescope aboard space station Salyut 1 in 1971.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Space telescopes avoid the filtering and distortion (scintillation) of electromagnetic radiation which they observe, and avoid light pollution which ground-based observatories encounter.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The best-known examples are Hubble Space Telescope and James Webb Space Telescope.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Cargo spacecraft are designed to carry cargo, possibly to support space stations' operation by transporting food, propellant and other supplies.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Automated cargo spacecraft have been used since 1978 and have serviced Salyut 6, Salyut 7, Mir, the International Space Station and Tiangong space station.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Some spacecraft can operate as both a crewed and uncrewed spacecraft.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] For example, the Buran spaceplane could operate autonomously but also had manual controls, though it never flew with crew onboard.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Other dual crewed/uncrewed spacecraft include: SpaceX Dragon 2, Dream Chaser, and Tianzhou.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] A communications satellite is an artificial satellite that relays and amplifies radio telecommunication signals via a transponder; it creates a communication channel between a source transmitter and a receiver at different locations on Earth.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Communications satellites are used for television, telephone, radio, internet, and military applications.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Others form satellite constellations in low Earth orbit, where antennas on the ground have to follow the position of the satellites and switch between satellites frequently.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The high frequency radio waves used for telecommunications links travel by line of sight and so are obstructed by the curve of the Earth.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The purpose of communications satellites is to relay the signal around the curve of the Earth allowing communication between widely separated geographical points.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Communications satellites use a wide range of radio and microwave frequencies.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] To avoid signal interference, international organizations have regulations for which frequency ranges or "bands" certain organizations are allowed to use.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] This allocation of bands minimizes the risk of signal interference.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Cargo or resupply spacecraft are robotic spacecraft that are designed specifically to carry cargo, possibly to support space stations' operation by transporting food, propellant and other supplies.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] As of 2023, three different cargo spacecraft are used to supply the International Space Station: Russian *Progress*, American SpaceX Dragon 2 and Cygnus.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Chinese *Tianzhou* is used to supply Tiangong space station.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Space probes are robotic spacecraft that are sent to explore deep space, or astronomical bodies other than Earth.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] They are distinguished from landers by the fact that they work in open space, not on planetary surfaces or in planetary atmospheres.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Being robotic eliminates the need for expensive, heavy life-support systems (the Apollo crewed Moon landings required the use of the Saturn V rocket that cost over a billion dollars per launch, adjusted for inflation) and so allows for lighter, less expensive rockets.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Space probes have visited every planet in the Solar System and Pluto, and the Parker Solar Probe has an orbit that, at its closest point, is in the Sun's chromosphere.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] There are five space probes that are escaping the Solar System, these are *Voyager 1*, *Voyager 2*, *Pioneer 10*, *Pioneer 11*, and *New Horizons*.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The identical Voyager probes, weighing 721.9 kilograms (1,592 lb), were launched in 1977 to take advantage of a rare alignment of Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus and Neptune that would allow a spacecraft to visit all four planets in one mission, and get to each destination faster by using gravity assist.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] In fact, the rocket that launched the probes (the Titan IIIE) could not even send the probes to the orbit of Saturn, yet *Voyager 1* is travelling at roughly 17 km/s (11 mi/s) and *Voyager 2* moves at about 15 km/s (9.3 mi/s) kilometres per second as of 2023.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] In 2012, *Voyager 1* exited the heliosphere, followed by *Voyager 2* in 2018.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] *Voyager 1* actually launched 16 days after *Voyager 2* but it reached Jupiter sooner because *Voyager 2* was taking a longer route that allowed it to visit Uranus and Neptune, whereas *Voyager 1* did not visit Uranus or Neptune, instead choosing to fly past Saturn’s satellite Titan.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] As of August 2023, *Voyager 1* has passed 160 astronomical units, which means it is over 160 times farther from the Sun than Earth is.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] This makes it the farthest spacecraft from the Sun.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] *Voyager 2* is 134 AU away from the Sun as of August 2023.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] NASA provides real time data of their distances and data from the probe’s cosmic ray detectors.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Because of the probe’s declining power output and degradation of the RTGs over time, NASA has had to shut down certain instruments to conserve power.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The probes may still have some scientific instruments on until the mid-2020s or perhaps the 2030s.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] After 2036, they will both be out of range of the Deep Space Network.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] A space telescope or space observatory is a telescope in outer space used to observe astronomical objects.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Space telescopes avoid the filtering and distortion of electromagnetic radiation which they observe, and avoid light pollution which ground-based observatories encounter.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] They are divided into two types: satellites which map the entire sky (astronomical survey), and satellites which focus on selected astronomical objects or parts of the sky and beyond.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Space telescopes are distinct from Earth imaging satellites, which point toward Earth for satellite imaging, applied for weather analysis, espionage, and other types of information gathering.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] A lander is a type of spacecraft that makes a soft landing on the surface of an astronomical body other than Earth.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Some landers, such as *Philae* and the Apollo Lunar Module, land entirely by using their fuel supply, however many landers (and landings of spacecraft on Earth) use aerobraking, especially for more distant destinations.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] This involves the spacecraft using a fuel burn to change its trajectory so it will pass through a planet (or a moon's) atmosphere.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Drag caused by the spacecraft hitting the atmosphere enables it to slow down without using fuel, however this generates very high temperatures and so adds a requirement for a heat shield of some sort.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Space capsules are a type of spacecraft that can return from space at least once.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] They have a blunt shape, do not usually contain much more fuel than needed, and they do not possess wings unlike spaceplanes.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] They are the simplest form of recoverable spacecraft, and so the most commonly used.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The first such capsule was the Vostok capsule built by the Soviet Union, that carried the first person in space, Yuri Gagarin.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Other examples include the Soyuz and Orion capsules, built by the Soviet Union and NASA, respectively.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Spaceplanes are spacecraft that are built in the shape of, and function as, airplanes.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The first example of such was the North American X-15 spaceplane, which conducted two crewed flights which reached an altitude of over 100 kilometres (62 mi) in the 1960s.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] This first reusable spacecraft was air-launched on a suborbital trajectory on July 19, 1963.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The first reusable orbital spaceplane was the Space Shuttle orbiter.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The first orbiter to fly in space, the Space Shuttle *Columbia*, was launched by the USA on the 20th anniversary of Yuri Gagarin's flight, on April 12, 1981.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] During the Shuttle era, six orbiters were built, all of which have flown in the atmosphere and five of which have flown in space.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] *Enterprise* was used only for approach and landing tests, launching from the back of a Boeing 747 SCA and gliding to deadstick landings at Edwards AFB, California.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The first Space Shuttle to fly into space was *Columbia*, followed by *Challenger*, *Discovery*, *Atlantis*, and *Endeavour*.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] *Endeavour* was built to replace *Challenger* when it was lost in January 1986.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] *Columbia* broke up during reentry in February 2003.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The first autonomous reusable spaceplane was the *Buran*-class shuttle, launched by the USSR on November 15, 1988, although it made only one flight and this was uncrewed.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] This spaceplane was designed for a crew and strongly resembled the U.S.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Space Shuttle, although its drop-off boosters used liquid propellants and its main engines were located at the base of what would be the external tank in the American Shuttle.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Lack of funding, complicated by the dissolution of the USSR, prevented any further flights of Buran.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The Space Shuttle was subsequently modified to allow for autonomous re-entry in case of necessity.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Per the Vision for Space Exploration, the Space Shuttle was retired in 2011 mainly due to its old age and high cost of program reaching over a billion dollars per flight.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The Shuttle's human transport role is to be replaced by SpaceX's SpaceX Dragon 2 and Boeing's CST-100 Starliner.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Dragon 2's first crewed flight occurred on May 30, 2020.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The Shuttle's heavy cargo transport role is to be replaced by expendable rockets such as the Space Launch System and ULA's Vulcan rocket, as well as the commercial launch vehicles.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Scaled Composites' SpaceShipOne was a reusable suborbital spaceplane that carried pilots Mike Melvill and Brian Binnie on consecutive flights in 2004 to win the Ansari X Prize.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The Spaceship Company built a successor SpaceShipTwo.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] A fleet of SpaceShipTwos operated by Virgin Galactic was planned to begin reusable private spaceflight carrying paying passengers in 2014, but was delayed after the crash of VSS *Enterprise*.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The Space Shuttle is a retired reusable Low Earth Orbital launch system.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The orbiter was a spaceplane that was launched at NASA’s Kennedy Space Centre and landed mainly at the Shuttle Landing Facility, which is part of Kennedy Space Centre.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] A second launch site, Vandenberg Space Launch Complex 6 in California, was revamped so it could be used to launch the shuttles, but it was never used.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The launch system could lift about 29 tonnes (64,000 lb) into an eastward Low Earth Orbit.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Each orbiter weighed roughly 78 tonnes (172,000 lb), however the different orbiters had differing weights and thus payloads, with *Columbia* being the heaviest orbiter, *Challenger* being lighter than *Columbia but* still heavier than the other three.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The orbiter structure was mostly composed of aluminium alloy.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The orbiter had seven seats for crew members, though on STS-61-A the launch took place with 8 crew onboard.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The orbiters had 4.6 metres (15 ft) wide by 18 metres (59 ft) long payload bays and also were equipped with a 15.2 metres (50 ft) CanadaArm1, an upgraded version of which is used on the International Space Station.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The orbiter was manually operated, though an autonomous landing system was added while the shuttle was still on service.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] It had an in orbit maneouvreing system known as the Orbital Manoeuvring System, which used the hypergolic propellants monomethylhydrazine (MMH) and dinitrogen tetroxide, which was used for orbital insertion, changes to orbits and the deorbit burn.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Though the shuttle’s goals were to drastically decrease launch costs, it did not do so, ending up being much more expensive than similar expendable launchers.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] This was due to expensive refurbishment costs and the external tank being expended.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Once a landing had occurred, the SRBs and many parts of the orbiter had to be disassembled for inspection, which was long and arduous.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Furthermore, the RS-25 engines had to be replaced every few flights.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Each of the heat shielding tiles had to go in one specific area on the orbiter, increasing complexity more.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Adding to this, the shuttle was a rather dangerous system, with fragile heat shielding tiles, some being so fragile that one could easily scrape it off by hand, often having been damaged in many flights.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] After 30 years in service from 1981 to 2011 and 135 flights, the shuttle was retired from service due to the cost of maintaining the shuttles, and the 3 remaining orbiters (the other two were destroyed in accidents) were prepared to be displayed in museums.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Some spacecraft do not fit particularly well into any of the general spacecraft categories.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Starship is a spacecraft and second stage under development by American aerospace company SpaceX.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Stacked atop its booster, Super Heavy, it composes the identically named Starship super heavy-lift space vehicle.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The spacecraft is designed to transport both crew and cargo to a variety of destinations, including Earth orbit, the Moon, Mars, and potentially beyond.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] It is intended to enable long duration interplanetary flights for a crew of up to 100 people.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] It will also be capable of point-to-point transport on Earth, enabling travel to anywhere in the world in less than an hour.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Furthermore, the spacecraft will be used to refuel other Starship vehicles to allow them to reach higher orbits to and other space destinations.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Elon Musk, the CEO of SpaceX, estimated in a tweet that 8 launches would be needed to completely refuel a Starship in low Earth orbit, extrapolating this from Starship's payload to orbit and how much fuel a fully fueled Starship contains.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] To land on bodies without an atmosphere, such as the Moon, Starship will fire its engines and thrusters to slow down.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The Mission Extension Vehicle is a robotic spacecraft designed to prolong the life on another spacecraft.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] It works by docking to its target spacecraft, then correcting its orientation or orbit.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] This also allows it to rescue a satellite which is in the wrong orbit by using its own fuel to move its target to the correct orbit.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The project is currently managed by Northrop Grumman Innovation Systems.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The first launched on a Proton rocket on 9 October 2019, and did a rendezvous with Intelsat-901 on 25 February 2020.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] It will remain with the satellite until 2025 before the satellite is moved to a final graveyard orbit and the vehicle does a rendezvous with another satellite.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The other one launched on an Ariane 5 rocket on 15 August 2020.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] A spacecraft astrionics system comprises different subsystems, depending on the mission profile.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Attached to the bus are typically payloads.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The attitude control subsystem permits proper pointing for the science objective, sun pointing for power to the solar arrays and Earth pointing for communications.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Guidance refers to the calculation of the commands (usually done by the CDH subsystem) needed to steer the spacecraft where it is desired to be.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The C&DH subsystem receives commands from the communications subsystem, performs validation and decoding of the commands, and distributes the commands to the appropriate spacecraft subsystems and components.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] or transmission to the ground via the communications subsystem.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Other functions of the CDH include maintaining the spacecraft clock and state-of-health monitoring.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Spacecraft need an electrical power generation and distribution subsystem for powering the various spacecraft subsystems.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] are frequently used to generate electrical power.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Electrical power is sent through power conditioning equipment before it passes through a power distribution unit over an electrical bus to other spacecraft components.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] as well as (if subject to reentry) in the presence of plasmas.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Depending on mission profile, spacecraft may also need to operate on the surface of another planetary body.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] can be passive, dependent on the selection of materials with specific radiative properties.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] such as louvers to control temperature ranges of equipments within specific ranges.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] subsystem, depending on whether or not the mission profile calls for propulsion.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] spacecraft is an example of a spacecraft that does not have a propulsion subsystem.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] A propulsion system is also needed for spacecraft that perform momentum management maneuvers.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The thermal control system interfaces with the propulsion subsystem by monitoring the temperature of those components, and by preheating tanks and thrusters in preparation for a spacecraft maneuver.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] Spacecraft must be engineered to withstand launch loads imparted by the launch vehicle, and must have a point of attachment for all the other subsystems.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] , and landing on the surface of another planetary body.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] The payload depends on the mission of the spacecraft, and is typically regarded as the part of the spacecraft "that pays the bills".
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] is vital to the operation of the spacecraft.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] to radiate signals to and receive signals from the spacecraft, and a voice and data communications network to connect all mission elements.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] , the exact orbit being dependent on the mission configuration.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/spacecraft] rocket, the rocket can be considered a spacecraft itself.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] A **star tracker** is an optical device that measures the positions of stars using photocells or a camera.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] As the positions of many stars have been measured by astronomers to a high degree of accuracy, a star tracker on a satellite or spacecraft may be used to determine the orientation (or attitude) of the spacecraft with respect to the stars.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] In order to do this, the star tracker must obtain an image of the stars, measure their apparent position in the reference frame of the spacecraft, and identify the stars so their position can be compared with their known absolute position from a star catalog.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] A star tracker may include a processor to identify stars by comparing the pattern of observed stars with the known pattern of stars in the sky.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] In the 1950s and early 1960s, star trackers were an important part of early long-range ballistic missiles and cruise missiles, in the era when inertial navigation systems (INS) were not sufficiently accurate for intercontinental ranges.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] Consider a Cold War missile flying towards its target; it initially starts by flying northward, passes over the arctic, and then begins flying southward again.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] From the missile's perspective, stars behind it appear to move closer to the southern horizon while those in front are rising.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] Before flight, one can calculate the relative angle of a star based on where the missile should be at that instant if it is in the correct location.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] That can then be compared to the measured location to produce an "error off" signal that can be used to bring the missile back onto its correct trajectory.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] Due to the Earth's rotation, stars that are in a usable location change over the course of a day and the location of the target.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] Generally, a selection of several bright stars would be used and one would be selected at launch time.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] For guidance systems based solely on star tracking, some sort of recording mechanism, typically a magnetic tape, was pre-recorded with a signal that represented the angle of the star over the period of a day.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] At launch, the tape was forwarded to the appropriate time.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] During the flight, the signal on the tape was used to roughly position a telescope so it would point at the expected position of the star.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] At the telescope's focus was a photocell and some sort of signal-generator, typically a spinning disk known as a chopper.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] The chopper causes the image of the star to repeatedly appear and disappear on the photocell, producing a signal that was then smoothed to produce an alternating current output.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] The phase of that signal could be compared to the phase of the chopper to determine angle to the star and this angle could be compared to the expected one on the tape to produce a guidance signal.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] Choppers combined with lock-in amplifiers can also help to provide immunity to noise.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] Star trackers were often combined with an INS.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] INS systems measure accelerations and integrate those over time to determine a velocity and, optionally, double-integrate to produce a location relative to its launch location.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] Even tiny measurement errors, when integrated, add up to an appreciable error known as "drift".
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] For instance, the N-1 navigation system developed for the SM-64 Navaho cruise missile drifted at a rate of 1 nautical mile per hour, meaning that after a two-hour flight the INS would be indicating a position 2 nautical miles (3.7 km; 2.3 mi) away from its actual location.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] This was outside the desired accuracy of about half a mile.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] In the case of an INS, the magnetic tape can be removed and those signals instead provided by the INS.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] The rest of the system works as before; the signal from the INS roughly positions the star tracker, which then measures the actual location of the star and produces an error signal.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] This signal is then used to correct the position being generated from the INS, reducing the accumulated drift back to the limit of the accuracy of the tracker.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] These "stellar inertial" systems were especially common from the 1950s through the 1980s, although some systems use it to this day.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] There also exist open projects designed to be used for the global CubeSat researchers' and developers' community.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] Star trackers, which require high sensitivity, may become confused by sunlight reflected from the spacecraft, or by exhaust gas plumes from the spacecraft thrusters (either sunlight reflection or contamination of the star tracker window).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] Star trackers are also susceptible to a variety of errors (low spatial frequency, high spatial frequency, temporal, ...) in addition to a variety of optical sources of error (spherical aberration, chromatic aberration, etc.).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] There are also many potential sources of confusion for the star identification algorithm (planets, comets, supernovae, the bimodal character of the point spread function for adjacent stars, other nearby satellites, point-source light pollution from large cities on Earth, ...).
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] There are roughly 57 bright navigational stars in common use.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] However, for more complex missions, entire star field databases are used to determine spacecraft orientation.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] These types of star catalogs can have thousands of stars stored in memory on board the spacecraft, or else processed using tools at the ground station and then uploaded.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/star-tracker] As space situational awareness sensors, star trackers can be used for space debris detection and for satellite identification.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/sun-sensor] A **Sun sensor** is a navigational instrument used by spacecraft to detect the position of the Sun.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/sun-sensor] Sun sensors are used for attitude control, solar array pointing, gyro updating, and fail-safe recovery.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/sun-sensor] In addition to spacecraft, Sun sensors find use in ground-based weather stations and Sun-tracking systems, and aerial vehicles including balloons and UAVs.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/sun-sensor] There are various types of Sun sensors, which differ in their technology and performance characteristics.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/sun-sensor] Sun presence sensors provide a binary output, indicating when the Sun is within the sensor's field of view.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/sun-sensor] Analog and digital Sun sensors, in contrast, indicate the angle of the Sun by continuous and discrete signal outputs, respectively.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/sun-sensor] In typical Sun sensors, a thin slit at the top of a rectangular chamber allows a line of light to fall on an array of photodetector cells at the bottom of the chamber.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/sun-sensor] A voltage is induced in these cells, which is registered electronically.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/sun-sensor] By orienting two sensors perpendicular to each other, the direction of the Sun can be fully determined.
[src:spacecraft-guidance/sun-sensor] Often, multiple sensors will share processing electronics.
